{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/0041421101A/1946041901/0463.xml":{"full_text":"Congress Asked To\nMake Probe Of\nPower Lobby\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014(Special)\u2014\nCong. Charles R. Savage of the state\nof Washington has called on congress\nto \"institute an investigation of the\nexpenditures and of the corrupt prac\ntices of certain lobbying organizations\nwhich have become a menace to dem\nocratic practices and a threat to na\ntional well-being.\" The congressman\nnames \"so-called reclamation associa\ntions, state and national, National\nAssociation of Electric companies and\nUnited States chamber of commerce\"\nand says \"they are now out to block\nfurther development of our great na\ntural resources and are seeking to get\ncontrol of many of them.\"\nIn presenting his request for an in\nvestigation and cleanup of power com\npany lobbyists, to the house, Congress\nman Savage said:\nConspiring to Rob People of Wealth\nBig money from power companies,\nrailroads, certain banking Interests,\nand other similar corporations is pour\ning into the coffers of the three lob\nbying organizations, and they are all\ncombining to rob the common people\nof the benefits of our great wealth\nof natural resources.\nThey tried for years to block the\ndevelopment of Grand Coulee dam\nand Bonneville dam in my state; they\nfought George Norris' efforts to get\nthe TVA started and now they are\ncentering their attention against the\nColumbia Valley Authority legislation.\nA small group of men, led by a\nformer Insul company official, is spear\nheading the organization, financing the\noperation of these three high-sound\ning organizations: the reclamation as\nsociation, the National Association of\nElectric companies, and the natural\nresources committee of the United\nStates chamber of commerce. They\nare tied together as tightly as two\npeas in a pod in their plan to rook\nthe American people.\nWould Repeat War I Steal\nfThey do not want the government\nto build dams, but if in spite of their\nopposition the government has built\na dam, they are determined that they\nwill buy the power at the bus bar.\nThey are determined to repeat their\nMuscle Shoals steal. At Muscle Shoals,\nthe government built a dam during\nWorld War I, and after the war these\npower companies bought power at the\nbus bar, paying the government less\nthan 2 mills per kilowatt-hour one\nfifth of a cent. And then they turned\naround and sold that power to the\npeople of that area, and how much\ndid they charge? They forced the peo\nple to pay 10 cents a kilowatt-hour\nfor that power right next to Wilson\ndam, 50 times as much as it cost\nthem.\nThat is the kind of private enter\nprise these lobbying organizations are\ntrying to perpetuate. They have a\nstrangle-hold on a good thing\none of the necessities of life elec\ntricity. They have a monopoly on it\nand they are determined to ride that\non\nmonopoly to the limit for all it is\nworth.\nWon't Support Candidates\nWho Favor Sales Tax\nRoosevelt County Farmer Union\nmembers at their quarterly convention\nin Poplar. March 30, voiced a strong\n\"no\" in opposition to any and all pro\nposals advocating the innovation of a\nsales tax, reports Mrs. W. Glenn\nSwank, secretary of the county or\nganization.\nThe union members also condemned\npropaganda being circulated\naround the state that a sales tax is\nnecessary to raise school funds, and\nrecommended that no one sup\nport any candidate for public office\nWHO favors a sales tax.\nthe\nDoctors Assessed $25 To\nFight Health Measure\nDETROIT.\u2014About 2,000 doctors in\nWayne County are paying an assess\nment of $25 apiece levied by the\nWayne County Medical Society, known\nas the medical trust, to fight the\nhealth provisions of the Wagner-Mur\nray-Dingell social security bill now\nbefore congress in Washington.\nBad Penny Back\nUpton Close, darling of the native\nfascists, is back on the air via the\nMutual network.\nTwice forced off the radio because\nof his pro-fascist leanings, the news\ncommentator is being sponsored by re\nactionary Merwin K. Hart's National\nEconomic council. Hart is a Franco\napologist.\nClose in March, 1941, said he saw\nlittle reason for having war with Ja\npan, but after Pearl Harbor he plug\nged a policy of trying to take the heat\noff Hitler by warning that \"our great\nest threat lies in the Pacific\nLegal Advertising\nCERTIFICATE\nIn Compliance With Section S019 of\nthe Revised Coden of Montana of 1933\nThis is to certify that PAUL L. HOL\nENSTEIN and ALFRED F. DOUGHER\nTY are copartners in and joint owners\nin that certain business known as\nWESTERN STATES DISTRIBUTORS\nand that said name is a fictitious name:\nthat the principal place of business of\nsaid business is Helena, Lewis and\nClark County, Montana: that the names\nin full of the members of such copart\nnership and their places of residence\nare as follows: PAUL L. HOLENSTEIN,\n725 Dearborn Avenue, Helena, Montana;\nand ALFRED F. DOUGHERTY, 512\nNorth Rodney. Helena, Montana.\nPAUL L. HOLENSTEIN\nALFRED F. DOUGHERTY\nState of Montana,\nCounty of Lewis and Clark, ss.\nOn this twenty-eighth day of March,\nA. D. 1946, before me, CLARENCE\nHANLEY, a Notary Public, personally\nappeared PAUL L. HOLENSTEIN and\nALFRED F, DOUGHERTY, known to\nme to be the persons whose signatures\nare affixed to the foregoing instrument\nand acknowledged to me they executed\nth same.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF, I have\nhereunto set my hand and affixed my\nnotarial seal this twenty-eighth day of\nMarch. A D. 1946.\nCLARENCE HANLEY,\nNotary Public in and for the\nState of Montana, residing at\nHelena, Montana.\nMy commission expires Sept. 25, 1946\nPubl. Mar. 29, Apr. 6. 12, 19, 1946\n(Seal)\nFigures Give Lie To NAIV\nClaim That OPA Stifles\nProfits\nThe NAM and the other lobbies\ndriving for an end to price control\nsay OPA ceilings are a threat to pri\nvate enterprise, make it Impossible\nfor business to get a decent profit\nand therefore stifle production. Here\nare statistics from the Departments of\nLabor and Commerce that show the\nper cent gain in profits all these poor\ncompanies showed in 1944, under OPA,\nover 1936-39. Profits in 1946 were as\nhigh or higher than in 1944, statistics\nso far compiled show, and with no\nexcess profits tax, will be even higher\nin 1946.\nPercent gain in\n1944 profits over\naverage 1936-39\n464%\n185%\n339%\n398%\n.1,324%\n152%\n450%\n730%\n590%\n270%\nHardware retailers\nSmall furniture stores\nVariety chain stores\nMen's apparel stores\nDepartment stores.\nChain grocery stores\nAll manufacturing\nTextile and leather\nMetals and products\nBuilding materials\nFood, beverage and tobacco.. 200%\nMANY JOBLESS IN L. A.\nLOS ANGELES.\u2014There are three\npersons unemployed for every five\nwith jobs in industry and local stores\nin Los Angeles County, figures kept\nby the United States Employment\nservice indicate. Unemployment will\nreach between 400,000 and 500,000 be\nfore the year is over.\nHe Who Pays\u2014\n(Continued from Pago One)\nUnion Farmer,\" reporting on the Den\nver, 1944 meeting of the national rec\nlamation association, had this to say\nabout the registration list. \"There\nwere about 20 persons who registered\nas from private power companies\nthroughout the West; a good many\nmore 'observers' from private power\ncompanies who did not register. There\nwere approximately as many regis\ntered as representing Western rail\nroads, likewise unregistered 'observ\ners.'\n\"There were approximately as many\nrepresenting chambers of commerce\nand other businessmen's bodies, in\ncluding the United States chamber of\ncommerce itself. There were more\nthan 100, at least, federal employees\nand officials of federal bureaus. There\nwere at least that many representa\ntives of state governments, including\nwater and irrigation commissioners.\nThere were businessmen of all types,\nrepresenting various businesses in the\nirrigation country. The new president\nof the association is a contractor.\"\nLet us repeat: anybody has the right\nto attend or support the organization\nin which he is interested or has an\n\"interest.\" But let us also repeat; he\nwho pays the fiddler calls the tune.\nBunch of Charlie McCarthys\nI personally should like to see the\nlist of contributors to the Missouri\nValley Development association. Also\nthe contributors to the Columbia Basin\nProtective association, now more\nhappily named the Northwest Region\nal Development association. I should\nthen have, I think, incontrovertible\nproof tor what is now only a good\nhunch: that the anti-MVA and the anti\nCVA campaign managers and orators\nare a bunch of Charlie McCarthys.\nThe trouble is that in most cases\nwe cannot\u2014unless we are a congres\nsional committee\u2014get the list of con\ntributors. We can only guess.\nRight now, however, there is one\nsituation right here in Montana that\ndoes not have to guess about. I re\nfer to the proposal by Fred Bennion of\nthe Taxpayers' association to finance\nthis summer a study of the tax situ\nation of Montana schools. The gover\nnor's commission, authorized by the\nlegislature, must report in November.\nBennion's privately endowed \"research\nspecialists\" will hand in their objec\ntive and impartial study of the\ntax situation in Montana in Septem\nber or October. Even assuming the\nimpossible that is, that the report\nwill not be \"Bennionized.\"\u2014Look what\na pressure such a report coming at\nsuch a time will exert on the members\nof the commission! I, for one, feel\nthat the Bennion report\u2014let us be\nfrank and call it that\u2014will be another\n1\nShip to the\nOpen Competitive Market\nj\nThrough your own agency\nThe Farmers Union Live Stock\nCommission Company\n\nI\nSo. St. Paul, Minn., West Fargo, N.D., Billings, Mont.\nWHERE\nThere Is buyer Competition.\nLivestock is sold on it's own merits.\nLivestock is well sold.\nLivestock is well handled.\nLivestock is in safe hands.\nOther livestock producers, like yourself,\nrealize the advantage of group action\nover individual efforts.\n\nShippers to this, your own agency\n\nThe\n\nFarmers Union Live Stock\nCommission Company\nI\nI\nSo. St. Paul, Minn., West Fargo, N.D., Billings, Mont.\nand shippers to all other Farmers Union agencies in the\nMississippi Valley are all working together for their mutual benefit.\nIN CO-OPERATION THERE IS STRENGTH\nCo-ops Help Break\nUp Monopolies,\nSays Arnold\nCOLUMBUS, Ohio. (CNS) The\ngovernment anti trust laws can't do\nthe whole job of breaking up monop\nolies. New businesses\u2014such as Co\noperatives\u2014must be ready to step into\neach new field of enterprise as it is\nopened, Thurman Arnold, associate\njustice, court of appeals for the Dis\ntrict of Columbia, told 2,000 policy\nholders, agents and visitors at the\nannual meetings of the Farm Bureau\ngroup of insurance companies meeting\nhere April 4.\nJudge Arnold said that he felt Co\noperatives are the most promising in\nstitutions for bringing real free enter\nprise into those areas now dominated\nby monopoly. The greatest value of\nCo-operative enterprise is not the di\nrect saving from actual operations, but\nthe indirect value of policing profit\nbusiness to keep it from becoming\nmonopolistic, the former assistant at\ntorney general declared.\nCites III Effects of Monopolies\nJudge Arnold pointed to several in\nstances of monopolistic business prac\ntice in the fields of transportation,\nfinance and manufacturing and cited\ntheir ill effects -on individual consum\ners and on the economy in general.\n\"Government,\" he declared, \"must\nstep in and break these log jams of\nmonopoly and open the way for free\ncompetition. The highways to business\nopportunity must be kept free if we\nare to have a prosperous and expand\ning economy.\"\nIn concluding, Judge Arnold ex\npressed confidence that America will\nretain free enterprise and the free\nmarket, and that the nation will move\non to undreamed levels of plenty and\nsecurity.\n(Continued from Piik\u00ab One)\nprices for the last 25 years. With\nwheat surpluses in Canada and the\nUnited States\u2014shipped out and eaten\nby the starving souls in Europe am\nAsia\u2014those surpluses will not be a\nheavy weight on wheat prices during\nthe period ahead.\n100 Million Bushels Needed\nIt mass starvation is to be avoided\nit is imperative that a hundred mil\nlion bushels of wheat be on its way\nto Europe and Asia within the next\n30 days. Conservative estimates some\nweeks back placed at 125 million\nbushels, the amount of wheat in stor\nage on American farms. More recent\nestimates place a storage figure for\nNorth Dakota at 85 million bushels,\nand Montana at 30 million, with na\ntional surplus in storage at probably\nwell over 150 million bushels.\nDuring March, 347,000 tons of wheat\nwere shipped overseas, whereas there\nwas a need for shipping of 700,000\ntons. Unless shipments can be pyra\nmided during the next month drastic\nration reductions for these millions\nwill be forced upon UNRRA. Such\nfurther reductions now will mean that\nrelief will have to be continued for\nanother year. The people on any furth\ner reduced rations will be unable to\nwork in the fields or in the mines or\neven in industry.\nSchedule of Wheat-Loan Meetings\nQualified speakers will meet with\nMontana fanners to explain the wheat\nloan program at the following places:\nApril 26\u2014Cut Bank, Glacier County;\nGreat Palls, Cascade; Stanford, Judith\nBasin; Plenty wood, Sheridan; Glen\ndive, Dawson; Hardin, Big Horn.\nApril 27\u2014Galata, Toole county; Fort\nBenton, Chouteau; Lewistown, Fer\ngus; Scobey, Daniels; Sidney, Rich\nland; Hysham, Treasure.\nApril 29\nJoplin, Pondera county;\nHavre, Hill; Roundup, Musselshell and\nGolden Valley; Opheim, North Valley;\nCircle, McCone; Terry, Prairie.\nApril 30\u2014Conrad, Pondera county;\nChinook, Blaine; Billings, Yellow\nstone: Glasgow, South Valley; Jordan,\nGarfield; Baker, Fallon.\nMay 1 Fairfield, Teton county;\nMalta, Phillips; Columbus, Stillwater;\nWolf Point, Roosevelt.\ncase of \"he who pays the fiddler calls\nthe tune.\"\nM. P. Moe Points\u2014\n(Continued from Page One)\ning any reason for such failure.\nSmith of CIO Present\nFrom the CIO, we invited Sylvester\nGraham and Mike Lacey. Mike* Lacey\ncame to the office and expressed re\ngret that he could not be here because\nboth he and Sylvester Graham were\nholding an executive meeting in Bill\nings, but Mr. Smith, then president of\nthe CIO local in East Helena, partici\npated and acted as one of the chair\nmen of one of the sections.\n(b) The second incident I wish to\npoint out is the one which took place\nwhen the committees on education of\nthe house and senate of the Montana\nlegislature in its 1945 session called\na hearing on the teachers' retirement\nproposal.\nIt is interesting to note that the op\nposition to teachers'\nretirement,\nwhich appeared at the hearing, was\nmade up of the following three per\nsons: Fred Bennlon, secretary of the\nMontana\nTaxpayers'\nJames Graham, president of the Mon\ntana Federation of Labor; and Miss\nMary McNelis, president of the Teach\ners' Union at Butte.\nMiss Mary McNelis stated, however,\nclearly that the Butte Teachers' Un\nion would favor the teachers' retire\nment plan as provided in H.B. 65 it\nthe legislature could not provide $250,\n000 for each of the two years and a\nconstitutional amendment to make the\nteachers' retirement system a consti\ntutional amendment.\nSince the hearing was held, three\ndays after the deadline for introducing\nbills, Mr. Graham's proposal of\nstitutional amendment appeared to\nas a sham and an attempt to destroy\nteachers' retirement in Montana.\nAssociation:\na con\nAsks Election of Fair-Minded\nOfficials\nThis is not a personal criticism\nattack on my part. It is merely giving\nyou incidents as they actually hap\nor\n1\nThe Farmer Goes To Town\ners through co-operation have been the salva\ntion of many small communities. There are\ntowns that would only be a whistle stop without\nCo-operatives.\nThat's been the history everywhere.\nWherever farmers have built their Co-opera\ntives, they have helped to keep trade in the\ncommunity. After all having a good trading\ncenter is not just a question of the size of the\ntown, but the number of people who come there\nto trade. Where farmers have a Co-op, whether\nit is a grain elevator, or a creamery or an oil\nstation, they make that town their all-around\ntrading center.\nThat is the story in many a small town in\nMontana. It's a story that's worth remembering.\nLook down any Main Street. The farmers'\ntrucks and cars are parked there. And it's his\nmoney that makes the cash registers ring.\nOnce there were people who said the small\ntown was done. But the farmer has helped them\nto stage a comeback.\nThe farmer depends on the small town in his\ncommunity to give him the kind of service he\nwants. And the merchants depend on the farmer\nfor their living. They have learned the value of\nco-operation. As a matter of fact the farmers\nare the people who have caught the vision and\nunderstanding of Co-ops better than any other\ngroup.\nIn the early days there were people who\ncalled Co-operatives a \"town killer\". But farm\nThis space provided by the following Co-operatives:\nEQUITY CO-OPERATIVE ASSOCIATION\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Peerless, Montana\nof Brady, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL SUPER SERVICE STATION\nPOWER FARMERS ELEVATOR COMPANY\nof Power, Montana\nof Glasgow, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Williston, North Dakota\nFARMERS UNION GRAIN COMPANY\nof Poplar, Montana\nFARMERS UNION CO-OP CREAMERY\nEQUITY CO-OPERATIVE ASSN. OF HARLEM\nBranch Stations in Hogeland and Turner, Montana\nChinook, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION LIVE STOCK COMMISSION CO.\nUnion Stock Yards\nRoy, Montana\nSouth St. Paul, Minn.\nBillings, Montana\nWINIFRED FARMERS OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nWinifred, Montana\nLewistown, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION CO-OP DAIRYMEN'S ASSN.\nof Glendive, Montana\nof Ravalli County, Stevensville, Montana\nFARMERS UNION EXCHANGE\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nKalispell, Montana\nof Belt, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION MERCANTILE COMPANY\nof Plentywood, Montana\nof Dodson, Montana\nTHE FARMERS UNION\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nin Froid, Montana\nof Valier, Montana\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR AND OIL CO.\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nof Chinook, Montana\nof Pendroy, Montana\nFARMERS UNION GRAIN COMPANY\n-FARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Peerless, Montana\nof Joplin, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Wolf Point, Montana\nFARMERS UNION CO-OP OIL COMPANY\nof Richey, Montana\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nof Rudyard, Montana\nof Joplin, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Opheim, Montana\nof Circle, Montana\nFARMERS UNION ELEVATOR COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION TRADING COMPANY\nWolf Point, Montana\nof Butte, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Havre, Montana\nof Flaxvllle, Montana\nEQUITY CO-OPERATIVE ASSOCIATION\nFARMERS UNION GRAIN SUPPLY COMPANY\nof Geraldine, Montana\nBillings, Montana\nFARMERS UNION TRADING COMPANY\nTHE FARMERS CO-OP OIL SUPPLY CO.\nof Richey, Montana\nof Conrad, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Nashua, Montana\nof Geyser, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL SUPPLY COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Hinsdale, Montana\nof Townsend, Montana\nEDUCATIONAL CO-OPERATIVE PUBLISHING CO.\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nof Helena, Montana\nof Lindsay, Montana\nFARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY\nFARMERS UNION SUPER SERVICE\nof Great Falls, Montana\nof Chinook, Montana\nCommission To\u2014\n(Continued from Pagre One)\nlabor is $1.20 per hour; intermediate\ngrade labor, $0.825 and $0.95 per hour.\nUnskilled labor, $0.66 per hour. Un\nskilled labor shall be obtained from\nlists prepared by agencies designated\nby the United States Employment\nservice.\nThe above mentioned wage scales\nare minimum wage scales only; in ac\ncordance with Revised Codes of Mon\ntana, 1935, the contractor must fur\nther pay the prevailing rate of wages\nin effect as paid in the county seat\nof the county in which the work is\nbeing performed, for each and every\nposition for which is higher than that\nspecified in the special provisions.\nPreference to Veterans\nIn the performance of all work un\nder these contracts, the contractor\nshall give such preferance to honor\nably discharged soldiers and sailors\nof the United States and to disabled\ncivilians recommended by the State\nRehabilitation Bureau as is provided\nfor in the Revised Codes of Montana,\n1935, as amended by the laws of 1937.\npened. I think that it is time that all\ngroups, whether it is labor or capi\ntal, clean house and elect officials\nwho are willing to consider all sides\nof a question and then support the pro\ngram that is for the best interests of\nall concerned.\nAfter all, we are one nation and\none people and should be working to\ngether for one democracy that will\nbe effective for all.\nI hope that you will give me the\nsame courtesy as you always have in\nprinting the information that I have\nsent to you. I appreciate that courtesy\nand wish to thank you in advance for\nits continuation.\nVery sincerely\u2014M. P. MOE, Execu\ntive Secretary.\nDEMAND THE UNION LABEL!\nTHE PEOPLE'S VOICE\nIt is owned by organized farmers and organized\nlabor. Its policy is to work for and protect the\ninterests of the \"little man\"; to expose corrup\ntion in government; to reveal the exploitation of\nthe common people by the special interests; to\nbetter the understanding of the common inter\nests of all workers on farm and in industry; to\nserve to outline the possibilities of building a\nbetter, more equitable social and economic order.\nWe need your support, and we believe that you\nneed the information you will get in The Peo\nple's Voice. If you are not already a subscriber,\nsend in your subscription TODAY. If you are a\nsubscriber, check the expiration date on address\nslip on your paper. If your subscription is due,\nsend it in TODAY.\nCo-operate with us. Let us make The People's\nVoice a powerful instrument for the betterment\nof the lot of the common man.\nFILL OUT THE COUPON BELOW AND ENCLOSE\n$2.00 per year.\nYOUR PAYMENT TODAY.\nPEOPLE'S VOICE PUBLISHING CO.\nBox 83?\nHELENA, MONTANA\nin payment of\nyears subscription to The People's Voice.\nEnclosed is\nNew\nRenewal\nName.\nAddress.","height":"21186","width":"16443"}}
